There we are.

64
00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Oh, is it Terence or Robert?

65
00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Terence. My official first name is Robert though, but I go as Terence.

66
00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
Okay, fantastic. Hi, Terence. Hey look, we've got five minutes, which goes pretty quickly.

67
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:17.000
So you want to leave time for questions, then keep your opening statements pretty brief and we have read your submission.

68
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
Fantastic. Thank you. So Kia ora and thank you very much for listening to me today. My name is Terence Harper.

69
00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
I live on the North Shore here in Auckland with my wife and four kids.

70
00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:35.000
And I'm here today because of my love and passion for the ocean and to emphasise to you that the ocean is a resource valued by people of all nationalities and all cultures.

71
00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And that it's our collective responsibility to protect it for future generations.

72
00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:47.000
I'm here to express my total opposition to this bill and request that the whole bill is thrown out and not progressed further.

73
00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:55.000
While it's stated to grow the value of the seafood sector exports, I believe we should be a country leading the world in environmental protection,

74
00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:04.000
not one that is going backwards and prioritise a short-term commercial gain at the cost of long-term ecological and economic health.

75
00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.000
If enacted, I feel you're destroying our New Zealand ocean for my children and for future generations.

76
00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:20.000
I can be a little bit more specific about some of the items in the bill, deeply concerned about simplifying and making a more responsive management system.

77
00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:28.000
This I feel can lead to changing catch limits really quickly to suit market conditions, but ultimately they will decimate those fish stocks,

78
00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:36.000
which are actually long-term things that need to be sorted. The biological reality of marine generation is long-term.

79
00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Also, formally oppose the amendment to revoke minimum size limits for those 10 different fish.

80
00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:51.000
I feel it's scientifically illogical to take smaller fish before they've had a chance and an opportunity to spawn.

81
00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:58.000
I also want to advocate for unifying a standard for catch, for commercial and recreational, to have one rule for commercial,

82
00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:05.000
for example, snapper 25 centimetres, yet for recreational 30 centimetres is in my view illogical,

83
00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
and we need to allow the time for those fish to breed and replenish in our waters.

84
00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:17.000
I also want to formally oppose the barriers to transparency and justice.

85
00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:22.000
If fishing boats are operating in international waters or New Zealand waters,

86
00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
they should be allowed to have full public scrutiny of their operations.

87
00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
If they're doing nothing wrong, they have nothing to hide.

88
00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And so if they're wanting to hide what they're doing, it feels to the public that they've got something to hide.

89
00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:40.000
So we should be able to view those cameras at any time via the OIA.

90
00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:48.000
Also allowing more than 20 days to get the evidence together and get a lawyer and stuff to oppose breaches,

91
00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
I think we need to keep allowing.

92
00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:58.000
I also want to formally oppose allowing bycatch to be dumped at sea, effectively legalising dumping.

93
00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:06.000
90% of our catch is exported for profit overseas, and yet many New Zealanders face food insecurity.

94
00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
I advocate for a no dumping policy where every fish caught is brought to port.

95
00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
If it cannot be sold under the quota system, for example, they are too small,

96
00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:21.000
they should be donated to local charities and food banks to feed our own communities.

97
00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:26.000
This would also incentivise commercial fishing to target the right size fish,

98
00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
because if they're catching a boatload or a hull worth of undersized fish,

99
00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
they can't sell it, that's bad economically.

100
00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So this incentivises them to catch the right size fish.

101
00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:44.000
So my feeling in conclusion, the ocean is a shared resource that must be managed with the vision beyond the next fiscal quarter.

102
00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Short-term commercial gains that decimate our stocks will inevitably lead to long-term economic failure.

103
00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:55.000
I urge this committee and to lead New Zealand towards genuine environmental protection,

104
00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:59.000
prioritising local food security over commercial flexibility.

105
00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Thank you, and I welcome any questions.

106
00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Thank you very much, Heron.

107
