114
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Hi, Candice. Hi.

115
00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Kia ora. Kia ora.

116
00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
So you've got five minutes. If you want to leave time for questions, that's entirely up to you.

117
00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
And yeah, this floor is yours. Thank you.

118
00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
So look, thank you for the opportunity to speak today.

119
00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:57.000
I strongly oppose the Fisheries Amendment Bill.

120
00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And in doing so, I've got four key concerns that, in my view, go to the heart of what this bill represents

121
00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
and why it shouldn't proceed.

122
00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:13.000
So firstly, I believe the bill is moving against the flow of the global tide.

123
00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:19.000
It represents a clear regression, in my view, in New Zealand's environmental management.

124
00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:27.000
If we look internationally, responsible countries and unions are strengthening protections, not weakening them.

125
00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:32.000
This includes the EU, our Pacific nations, and Australia.

126
00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Globally, governments, including this one, have committed to protect at least 30% of the ocean

127
00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:44.000
and to minimise the impacts of fishing on ecosystems through the Global Ocean Treaty.

128
00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:53.000
The common global theme is better protection, more selective fishing methods, and stronger oversight.

129
00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:00.000
New Zealand's built its identity on being clean, green, and environmentally responsible.

130
00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
But I believe that this bill moves us in the opposite direction.

131
00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:09.000
It reduces scrutiny, it weakens the safeguards,

132
00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:15.000
and it fails to address the real issue of indiscriminate fishing methods.

133
00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.000
So I believe that the bill's not just out of step with international best practice.

134
00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:28.000
It's actually out of step with what we say we stand for as New Zealanders.

135
00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:35.000
Secondly, in restricting access to information and onboard camera footage,

136
00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:41.000
the bill removes public scrutiny. Now that's a backward step.

137
00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Transparency is fundamental to public trust.

138
00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:50.000
It will mean that there's no meaningful accountability.

139
00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:56.000
We know from experience that transparency and monitoring changes behaviour.

140
00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
If we remove that transparency and public scrutiny,

141
00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:07.000
I believe it will undermine compliance and create an even greater sense of mistrust

142
00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
in our commercial fishing industry.

143
00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:18.000
Thirdly, the proposal to allow the capture and retention of undersized fish

144
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:23.000
is a significant step away from sustainability.

145
00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:30.000
The purpose of size limits is straightforward, to ensure that fish can reach maturity

146
00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
and breed before they are caught.

147
00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:41.000
By allowing the landing and capture and sale of previously discarded fish,

148
00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:46.000
you will only encourage the catching of undersized or non-target species.

149
00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
It will increase the by-catch.

150
00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:55.000
We now know that the EU's own landing policy has not driven the behavioural change

151
00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
that they had hoped for.

152
00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:04.000
So our regulatory focus should be on reducing the by-catch, not increasing it.

153
00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:10.000
Fourthly and in my view most importantly, this bill fails to address the real issue,

154
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.000
the non-selective and discriminate fishing methods.

155
00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:20.000
Large scale methods such as bottom trawling and other non-selective techniques

156
00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.000
capture juvenile fish before they breed.

157
00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:27.000
They result in significant by-catch of non-target species

158
00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:34.000
and they damage our marine habitats that are essential for sustaining fish populations.

159
00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.000
But this bill does nothing to address that.

160
00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:44.000
Instead it makes it easier to deal with the consequences of indiscriminate fishing.

161
00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And that's the wrong focus.

162
00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:52.000
I've seen over the course of my lifetime the significant depletion of fish stocks

163
00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.000
in the Hauraki Gulf and elsewhere.

164
00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:59.000
And my view is that this bill will exacerbate that.

165
00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:05.000
We now know more than ever the importance of protecting our marine ecosystem

166
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:08.000
to ensure the health of our planet.

167
00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.000
This bill is not based on sustainability objectives.

168
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:18.000
It's not based on sustainability objectives or on the protections that are required,

169
00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.000
which should be the focus of modern day fisheries reform.

170
00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.000
It's designed purely to increase profitability for a few.

171
00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
And it does appear manifestly corrupt.

172
00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:33.000
So I'm calling for a different approach.

173
00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:38.000
Rather than weakening safeguards, I believe that we should be strengthening

174
00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:41.000
monitoring and transparency.

175
00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.000
We should be maintaining protections that allow fish to reproduce.

176
00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And most importantly, to undertake an inquiry into how the commercial sector

177
00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:56.000
can transition towards a more selective fishing method.

178
00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And I think we can look to Australia for that.

179
00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
So in closing, this bill is not just a technical reform.

180
00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
It's a signal about what we value.

181
00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:15.000
Do we value short-term profit for a few or long-term sustainability that will benefit all?

182
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:20.000
So I'm urging the committee to reject the bill in its current form

183
00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:25.000
and instead to pursue reforms that genuinely protect our oceans, our fisheries,

184
00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:28.000
and the interests of our future generations.

185
00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
Thank you.

186
00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Thank you very much for your comprehensive and heartfelt summation, Candice.

187
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
I appreciate your time today.

